      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The technical steps are as follows:\n\n1. Anaerobic respiration in your muscles breaks down glucose to produce energy, releasing hydrogen ions (H+) and electrons.\n2. The hydrogen ions accumulate in your muscles, causing the pH level to drop (become more acidic).\n3. The decrease in pH triggers the activation of mechanoreceptors, which are specialized nerve endings that detect changes in muscle tension and length.\n4. The activated mechanoreceptors send signals to the spinal cord and brain, which interpret these signals as pain.\n5. The specific pain sensation is thought to be mediated by the activation of TRPV1 channels, which are pain receptors that are sensitive to changes in pH, temperature, and other stimuli.\n\nIn terms of the technical details, the decrease in pH triggers the activation of the NMDA receptor, a type of glutamate receptor that is involved in pain transmission. The NMDA receptor is activated by the binding of glutamate to its binding site, and this binding is facilitated by the decrease in pH, which reduces the inhibitory effects of magnesium ions on the receptor. This leads to an influx of calcium ions into the neuron, which triggers the activation of TRPV1 channels and the subsequent pain sensation.",
